to the editor re more than death fearing a muddled mind front page nov 11 a diagnosis of early stage alzheimer 's need not mean an abrupt end to quality of life last week the alzheimer 's association of which i am executive director held a conference on early stage alzheimer 's dozens of people with the disease bore testimony to the fact that a meaningful and satisfying life need not end with the diagnosis there may not be a cure yet but there are medical interventions that can help slow the progression of the disease 's symptoms there are also psychosocial programs that can help sustain a quality of life that was not possible just a decade ago anyone concerned that a loved one may be facing early stage alzheimer 's should seek a full medical evaluation by a qualified doctor explore existing treatment options and request a referral to the support services that are increasingly available john a jager new york nov 11 2002

